column15: Foreign Affairs\, Trade and Development Canada (DFATD),Affaires étrangères\, Commerce et Développement Canada (MAECD)
column17: Poverty Reduction Local Fund - Phase II,Fonds d'appui à la lutte contre la pauvreté - phase II
column20: The Poverty Reduction Local Fund - Phase II (FALP II) responds to proposals from non-governmental organizations (NGOs) and development associations active in Niger. The funded initiatives helped to build the institutional capacities of partner organizations and to give the poorest\, mainly women and children\, better access to social services and basic nutrition. FALP II focuses its support on the Maradi\, Tillaberi\, and Tahoua regions.,Le Fonds d'appui à la lutte contre la pauvreté\, phase II (FALP II) répond à des propositions d’organisations non gouvernementales (ONG) et d’associations de développement oeuvrant au Niger. Les initiatives ainsi appuyées ont contribué au renforcement des capacités institutionnelles des organisations partenaires et à un meilleur accès à des services sociaux ainsi qu'à une meilleure alimentation de base pour les populations les plus démunies\, principalement les femmes et les enfants. Le FALP II concentre ses appuis dans les régions de Maradi\, Tillabéri et Tahoua.

column108: Urban issues,Questions urbaines,Children's issues,Questions touchant les enfants,Adolescent (Youth) Issues,Questions touchant les adolescents (jeunes),Indigenous issues,Questions touchant les populations autochtones,ICT as a tool for development,Les TIC comme outils de développement
column212: Results achieved by this project as of March 2011 include: 1\,041 women in four communes of the Tahoua region have access to self-managed microcredit to carry out revenue-generating activities. 540 producers in the Maradi region\, including 150 women\, were trained at 27 field schools and have built their capacities in agricultural techniques. The members of 52 farmers’ organizations better understand their role and are actively involved in associations in their region. An integrated health centre has been established in Maradi and it provides quality health care to an estimated population of 10\,811. In the Tahoua region\, 7\,589 people have greater access to safe drinking water\, thanks to the building of three modern wells in Cheghamane\, Intoussa\, and Goumbi Danyayé\, as well as the rehabilitation of two wells in Fallali and Maraba Kao.,Parmi les résultats obtenus par le projet jusqu'en mars 2011 : 1 041 femmes de quatre communes de la région de Tahoua ont accès au micro-crédit autogéré pour mener des activités génératrices de revenus; 540 producteurs\, dont 150 femmes\, de la région de Maradi ont été formés dans 27 écoles sur le terrain et ont renforcé leurs compétences en techniques agricoles et les membres de 52 organisations paysannes connaissent mieux leur rôle et participent activement dans la vie associative de leur région. Un centre de santé intégré a été mis en place à Maradi et dispense des soins de santé de qualité à une population estimée à 10 811 personnes. Dans la région de Tahoua\, 7 589 personnes ont un accès accru à l’eau potable grâce à la construction de trois puits modernes à Cheghamane\, Intoussa et Goumbi Danyayé et à la réhabilitation de deux puits à Fallali et Maraba Kao.

column15: Swiss Agency for Development and Cooperation (SDC)
column17: Programme d’Hydraulique Rurale – Appui Au Secteur Eau et Assainissement (PHRASEA) Phase 2
column20: Moins de 50% des nigériens ont accès à l’eau potable et seuls 7% disposent de conditions d'assainissement de base. La croissance démographique galopante\, la dispersion de la population sur le territoire et la précarité des finances publiques sont des contraintes empêchant l'accès des populations à ces services de base. Le PHRASEA vient en appui aux efforts du gouvernement\, en misant sur la maitrise d’ouvrage des communes.

column17: Projet intercommunal eau et assainissement (canton d'Illéla - Niger)
column20: Le projet vise à améliorer durablement l'accès à l'eau et à l'assainissement dans les 4 communes du canton d'Illéla (Niger) en renforçant la gouvernance communale et intercommunale des services de l'eau et de l'assainissement (E&A)\, en favorisant l'accès à l'eau potable\, l'hygiène et à l'assainissement\, des populations des 4 communes et en structurant les opérateurs locaux de gestion du service E&A. Les bénéficiaires sonles populations des 23 villages touchés par le projet\, soit 30 000 personnes

column20: The various Apps in the toolbox can assist embassies in their efforts to create a business-enabling environment\, remove trade barriers and in matching local and Dutch business partners\, in order to shape the local implementation of the Dutch agenda for Aid\, Trade and Investment. Matchmaking\, Government to Government assistance\, training of managers and entrepreneurs\, trade missions to and from developing countries\, transfer of knowledge between educational or knowledge institutions such as universities in a given country and in the Netherlands are some examples of these initiatives.

column20: The Dutch Surge Support (DSS water) responds to the needs during water related disasters around the globe by deploying excellent experts from the Dutch water sector. With this facility the Netherlands aims to contribute to a better international response to water and sanitation related disasters and assist in building up knowledge in dealing with these emergencies. Netherlands Enterprise Agency administers DRR at the request of the Ministry of Foreign Affairs of The Netherlands and the Ministry of Infrastructure and Environment.

Netherlands Enterprise Agency administers DRR at the request of the Ministry of Foreign Affairs of The Netherlands and the Ministry of Infrastructure and Environment.

column20: The Facility for Infrastructure Development (ORIO) encourages public infrastructure development in upcoming markets and developing countries. Netherlands Enterprise Agency administers ORIO at the request of the Ministry of Foreign Affairs of The Netherlands.

column15: King Salman Humanitarian Aid and Relief Centre
column17: Providing drinking water in the Republic of Niger.
column20:
- Drilling of (163) surface wells ranging from (20 to 30 meters).
- Installation of 163 hand pumps.,1- Implementing sustainable activities to provide safe drinking water to (241\,880 beneficiaries) by digging (163) surface wells.
2- Contribute to reducing the percentage of diseases resulting from drinking contaminated water.
3- Providing water for livestock\, on which the economy of the population in the targeted areas depends.
4- To contribute to stabilizing the population and limiting desertion in order to obtain water sources.
5- Increasing sources of safe drinking water and personal use in dry areas.
6- An increase in the percentage of crop productivity in the targeted areas.,About (241\,880) beneficiaries have access to safe drinking water and daily use in each of the following areas (Dosso / Tillaberi / Tawa).
column27: King Salman Humanitarian Aid and Relief Centre,Al-Wafa World Organization

column15: King Salman Humanitarian Aid and Relief Centre
column17: Drilling (6) surface wells in Tlabéri\, Republic of Niger
column20: Providing potable water to the citizens of Niger by digging and preparing wells,Providing a source of safe water for drinking and personal use in the targeted areas with humanitarian needs\, reducing the rate of epidemic diseases\, supporting the economy by providing water for livestock\, which is a source of livelihood for the residents of the targeted areas\, limiting the migration of residents of the area and enhancing living there.,Providing drinking water for personal use to (60\,699) beneficiaries\, preserving livestock and enhancing the local and national economy\, in addition to limiting the spread of epidemic diseases and promoting personal hygiene in a clean and safe environment in the targeted areas.
column27: King Salman Humanitarian Aid and Relief Centre,Al-Wafa World Organization
